<subSubSection id="C304FCE67622FFE469901BF61138F9B2" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA1AF6D7622FFE469901BF61138F9B2" blockId="45.[151,1437,1143,1559]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE469901BF6135CFAA0" bold="true" box="[197,321,1259,1285]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE4681C1BF6102CFAA1" box="[329,561,1259,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE4681C1BF6102CFAA1" box="[329,561,1259,1284]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Hemipenthes morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46B9B1BF61174FAA1" box="[718,873,1259,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morioides">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46B9B1BF61174FAA1" box="[718,873,1259,1284]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46AF11BF61622FAA1" box="[932,1087,1259,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seminigra">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46AF11BF61622FAA1" box="[932,1087,1259,1284]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. seminigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE469C21A0F132DFA8E" box="[151,304,1298,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morioides">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE469C21A0F132DFA8E" box="[151,304,1298,1323]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the lack of aureoles in the wings. The European specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46D6F1A0F16B9FA8E" box="[1082,1188,1298,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46D6F1A0F16B9FA8E" box="[1082,1188,1298,1323]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, listed above, can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE4682E1A241009FAF7" box="[379,532,1337,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seminigra">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE4682E1A241009FAF7" box="[379,532,1337,1362]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. seminigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the cell 
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46BA01A24111DFAF7" box="[757,768,1337,1362]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">r</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46A541A541114FAF2" box="[769,777,1353,1367]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<number id="3DD6BD4A7622FFE46A541A541114FAF2" box="[769,777,1353,1367]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</emphasis>
not narrowed at wing margin and the margin epiphallus narrowed before apex in ventral view (
<figureCitation id="1325B3E87622FFE46B261A7F10D2FAD9" box="[627,719,1378,1404]" captionStart="FIGURES 77 – 78" captionStartId="45.[151,269,1069,1093]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,595,1026]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[151,1436,583,1044]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 77 – 78. Hemipenthes morio male terminalia. 77, lateral view; 78, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/187178/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number id="3DD6BD4A7622FFE46BF91A7F10D2FAD9" box="[684,719,1378,1404]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" value="78.0">78</number>
</figureCitation>
). But the specimens examined identified as 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46DBE1A7F1744FADE" box="[1259,1369,1378,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46DBE1A7F1744FADE" box="[1259,1369,1378,1403]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North 
<collectingCountry id="F309EFFD7622FFE469B61A941355FA06" box="[227,328,1417,1443]" name="United States of America" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">America</collectingCountry>
from Quebec, 
<collectingCountry id="F309EFFD7622FFE468AD1A941049FA06" box="[504,596,1417,1443]" name="Canada" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Canada</collectingCountry>
; Arizona, Idaho, Utah, Washington, 
<collectingCountry id="F309EFFD7622FFE46D541A941621FA06" box="[1025,1084,1417,1443]" name="United States of America" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">USA</collectingCountry>
are identical to those from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46C2A1A941310FA6C" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seminigra">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46C2A1A941310FA6C" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. seminigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
even in its genital characters 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46B261AAD10C2FA6C" box="[627,735,1456,1481]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46B261AAD10C2FA6C" box="[627,735,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been considered to be Holarctic in distribution but the evidence shown here indicates that 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46B661ACB1081FA4A" box="[563,668,1494,1519]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46B661ACB1081FA4A" box="[563,668,1494,1519]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in fact Palearctic; and the specimens determined as 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE7622FFE46C401ACB1763FA4A" box="[1301,1406,1494,1519]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis id="B96A737F7622FFE46C401ACB1763FA4A" box="[1301,1406,1494,1519]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">H. morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in North 
<collectingCountry id="F309EFFD7622FFE469B61AE01355F9B2" box="[227,328,1533,1559]" name="United States of America" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">America</collectingCountry>
